Here, we'll see how to take input in an ArrayList.

---

**Example: Take Marks of 5 Students as Input (Using ArrayList)**

```java
import java.util.Scanner;
import java.util.ArrayList;

class Seedit {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in); // Create a Scanner object

        ArrayList marks = new ArrayList<>(); // Step 1: Declare an ArrayList

        // Step 2: Take input for each element
        System.out.println("Enter marks of 5 students:");
        for (int i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
            marks.add(sc.nextInt()); // Read each mark from user
        }

        // Step 3: Print the entered marks
        System.out.println("You entered:");
        for (int i = 0; i < marks.size(); i++) {
            System.out.println("Student " + (i + 1) + ": " + marks.get(i));
        }

        sc.close(); // Close the scanner
    }
}
```

---

**Output:**
```java
You entered:
Student 1: 50
Student 2: 60
Student 3: 70
Student 4: 80
Student 5: 90
```

